Here's a full breakdown of what's going on:
What STS-12UC.EXE Is

This is STS-12, a vintage DOS BBS (Bulletin Board System) host program — the kind that ran on dedicated PCs connected to phone lines in the 80s/90s. "The Jungle" was likely the BBS's name. It has mail, chat, user accounts, sysop commands, dial-out, etc.
Why It Reboots

The BOUNDS errors in IDA are the smoking gun. The program contains deliberate far calls into ROM addresses:
Address in IDA	Target	What it is
seg041:00CA	F000:FFFF	x86 BIOS Reset Vector — literally reboots the machine
seg041:00CF	C000:0000	Video BIOS ROM
seg041:00D4	C800:0000	Hard disk controller BIOS ROM

The call to F000:FFFF is the reboot. STS-12 was designed to run on real 1980s/90s DOS hardware and used the BIOS reset vector as its shutdown/reboot mechanism (you can even see strings: "Fast Shutdown... reboot", "Catastrophic Shutdown (reboot, no disk buffer flush)").

When you run it today (even in DOSBox or a VM), it hits that call and resets the machine.
Fixing It in IDA
For the BOUNDS errors (far calls to ROM):

    In IDA, go to seg041:00CA, 00CF, 00D4
    The hint says "use manual arg" — right-click each call → Edit operand and manually set the target
    To properly analyze without crashing: add stub segments in IDA via Edit → Segments → Add segment for F000, C000, and C800 so IDA stops complaining

To prevent it from actually rebooting when run:

    NOP out the call at seg041:00CA (the F000:FFFF call) — replace the call far ptr 0F000h:0FFFFh bytes with 90 90 90 90 90 (NOPs)
    Or patch it to call a safe return instead

For the rest of the IDA errors:

    ALREADY — press U to undefine, then redefine
    BADSTACK — these retn N / retf N instructions are normal Pascal-calling-convention cleanup in 16-bit DOS code; edit each function (Alt+P) and set the correct purged bytes count

Bottom Line

The reboot isn't a bug — it's a feature of the original BBS software calling the hardware reset vector. To safely reverse-engineer it, you need to NOP that far call at seg041:00CA and add the missing ROM segments to IDA's segment list.

